<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<tt xml:lang="en-US"
  xmlns="http://www.w3.org/ns/ttml"
  xmlns:ttm="http://www.w3.org/ns/ttml#metadata"
  xmlns:tts="http://www.w3.org/ns/ttml#styling">
  <head>
    <metadata xmlns:ttm="http://www.w3.org/ns/ttml#metadata">
      <ttm:title>437100322 - 1_d38mgj7g - PID 1530551</ttm:title>
    </metadata>
    <styling>
      <style xml:id="basic" tts:textAlign="center" />
    </styling>
  </head>

  <body>
    <div style="basic">
        <p begin="00:00:00.000" end="00:00:05.300" tts:direction="ltr">Hello, visitors. We are at the final part
<br />of our design base camp,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:05.300" end="00:00:08.700" tts:direction="ltr">and that is the concept of Gestalt.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:08.700" end="00:00:10.760" tts:direction="ltr">You may not have heard that word before,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:10.760" end="00:00:13.660" tts:direction="ltr">but I'm confident that you've seen Gestalt
<br />in action.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:13.660" end="00:00:19.900" tts:direction="ltr">Gestalt comes from u Germany and it comes
<br />through a period of time in</p>
        <p begin="00:00:19.900" end="00:00:23.080" tts:direction="ltr">the 1940s and 50s when designers were
<br />really thinking</p>
        <p begin="00:00:23.080" end="00:00:27.460" tts:direction="ltr">about how customers and people were
<br />interacting with design.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:27.460" end="00:00:34.060" tts:direction="ltr">The phrase that came out of it is that the
<br />whole is greater than its parts,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:34.060" end="00:00:39.280" tts:direction="ltr">you may have heard that that concept is
<br />that if I see something,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:39.280" end="00:00:43.040" tts:direction="ltr">I see the whole first and not the
<br />individual parts.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:43.040" end="00:00:44.660" tts:direction="ltr">If I'm driving down the road,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:44.660" end="00:00:47.100" tts:direction="ltr">I'm going to see a house first,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:47.100" end="00:00:51.435" tts:direction="ltr">and then I might see a door or a window or
<br />a flower.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:51.435" end="00:00:53.910" tts:direction="ltr">So while the flower and door and</p>
        <p begin="00:00:53.910" end="00:00:56.510" tts:direction="ltr">window are important because they build
<br />the hole,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:56.510" end="00:00:58.430" tts:direction="ltr">the hole is what we see first.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:58.430" end="00:01:03.070" tts:direction="ltr">That's an important idea conceptually when
<br />we're working in design to be able</p>
        <p begin="00:01:03.070" end="00:01:05.810" tts:direction="ltr">to direct our audience to the insights</p>
        <p begin="00:01:05.810" end="00:01:08.950" tts:direction="ltr">that we're hoping that they'll see first.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:08.950" end="00:01:11.890" tts:direction="ltr">We're going to talk about five principles,
<br />proximity,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:11.890" end="00:01:16.530" tts:direction="ltr">similarity, enclosure, continuity and
<br />connection.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:16.530" end="00:01:18.830" tts:direction="ltr">When it comes to proximity,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:18.830" end="00:01:23.410" tts:direction="ltr">it's important to recognize that where the
<br />data lies,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:23.410" end="00:01:29.010" tts:direction="ltr">we'll already have an association that
<br />they are somehow similar or related.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:29.010" end="00:01:31.230" tts:direction="ltr">Here I have three different groups,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:31.230" end="00:01:34.590" tts:direction="ltr">and simply because I've got white space in
<br />between them,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:34.590" end="00:01:38.510" tts:direction="ltr">I see that these are somehow related to
<br />each other.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:38.510" end="00:01:41.790" tts:direction="ltr">Now, I could have completely different
<br />kinds of data in there.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:41.790" end="00:01:44.270" tts:direction="ltr">But because of that close proximity,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:44.270" end="00:01:47.950" tts:direction="ltr">there is something that I'm going to
<br />naturally infer from that.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:47.950" end="00:01:50.410" tts:direction="ltr">Now, as we go through these gestal
<br />principles,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:50.410" end="00:01:52.370" tts:direction="ltr">I want you to know that we're going</p>
        <p begin="00:01:52.370" end="00:01:57.780" tts:direction="ltr">from from least to greatest in terms of
<br />strength.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:57.780" end="00:02:01.100" tts:direction="ltr">Proximity is the lowest gestalt principle,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:01.100" end="00:02:03.640" tts:direction="ltr">but one that individuals will
<br />automatically</p>
        <p begin="00:02:03.640" end="00:02:06.600" tts:direction="ltr">have if I see these three clusters.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:06.600" end="00:02:10.060" tts:direction="ltr">If I want to break out with maybe this
<br />needs to be an insight,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:10.060" end="00:02:12.940" tts:direction="ltr">I have to do something to break that out.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:12.940" end="00:02:15.040" tts:direction="ltr">I can't just have that be by</p>
        <p begin="00:02:15.040" end="00:02:17.180" tts:direction="ltr">itself because I'm going to naturally
<br />believe that</p>
        <p begin="00:02:17.180" end="00:02:22.435" tts:direction="ltr">that data point belongs and is influenced
<br />by this particular group.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:22.435" end="00:02:26.130" tts:direction="ltr">So when I look at the cube of all these
<br />colors,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:26.130" end="00:02:29.150" tts:direction="ltr">as soon as I break maybe these two off,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:29.150" end="00:02:31.350" tts:direction="ltr">now that I see instead of one group,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:31.350" end="00:02:33.030" tts:direction="ltr">I have three groups.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:33.030" end="00:02:35.490" tts:direction="ltr">That's the power of proximity.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:35.490" end="00:02:37.590" tts:direction="ltr">On your note taking sheet,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:37.590" end="00:02:42.030" tts:direction="ltr">you can go ahead and color in those two
<br />other broke off pieces to show</p>
        <p begin="00:02:42.030" end="00:02:44.490" tts:direction="ltr">how proximity can really create</p>
        <p begin="00:02:44.490" end="00:02:47.610" tts:direction="ltr">a different way of looking at some of that
<br />data.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:47.610" end="00:02:49.670" tts:direction="ltr">The next one is similarity,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:49.670" end="00:02:52.350" tts:direction="ltr">and in this case, I still have those three
<br />groups,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:52.350" end="00:02:53.870" tts:direction="ltr">but now what do I have?</p>
        <p begin="00:02:53.870" end="00:02:57.590" tts:direction="ltr">I've used xs and squares to show this
<br />principle.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:57.590" end="00:03:00.870" tts:direction="ltr">Here's my question, which is stronger,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:00.870" end="00:03:05.690" tts:direction="ltr">the group that's cluser together or the xs
<br />that you see,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:05.690" end="00:03:08.250" tts:direction="ltr">which is the greater association.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:08.250" end="00:03:11.445" tts:direction="ltr">If you said xs, that would be correct.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:11.445" end="00:03:14.940" tts:direction="ltr">When we have this idea of similarity,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:14.940" end="00:03:18.820" tts:direction="ltr">it actually supersedes this principle of
<br />proximity.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:18.820" end="00:03:22.940" tts:direction="ltr">Somehow, now I'm saying these are in some
<br />way</p>
        <p begin="00:03:22.940" end="00:03:27.960" tts:direction="ltr">related in a tighter way than this space
<br />that has.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:27.960" end="00:03:30.720" tts:direction="ltr">Think about our scatter plots that we
<br />create</p>
        <p begin="00:03:30.720" end="00:03:34.880" tts:direction="ltr">or where we have maybe one dimension
<br />versus another dimension.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:34.880" end="00:03:38.060" tts:direction="ltr">Suddenly, we can use Gestalt as a way to
<br />say,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:38.060" end="00:03:41.340" tts:direction="ltr">these are all in the same family and these
<br />are all the same family,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:41.340" end="00:03:44.825" tts:direction="ltr">even though they overlap similar spaces.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:44.825" end="00:03:47.830" tts:direction="ltr">When it comes to the cube,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:47.830" end="00:03:51.390" tts:direction="ltr">all I need to do is use some contrasting
<br />tool like</p>
        <p begin="00:03:51.390" end="00:03:55.830" tts:direction="ltr">color to denote that even though this
<br />seems like this is one,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:55.830" end="00:03:58.910" tts:direction="ltr">I actually still have one two,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:58.910" end="00:04:01.430" tts:direction="ltr">actually. Let me go back.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:01.430" end="00:04:04.010" tts:direction="ltr">What I have is I</p>
        <p begin="00:04:04.010" end="00:04:11.030" tts:direction="ltr">have one because these are all the same
<br />color and shape, and then I have two.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:11.190" end="00:04:14.310" tts:direction="ltr">That's where your user is seeing.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:14.310" end="00:04:20.050" tts:direction="ltr">You can take a moment and fill that into
<br />the note taking, if you so choose.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:20.050" end="00:04:23.650" tts:direction="ltr">The next stop principle is this idea of
<br />enclosure.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:23.650" end="00:04:30.130" tts:direction="ltr">It has the E N. This is the idea that as
<br />soon as I close anything,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:30.130" end="00:04:32.410" tts:direction="ltr">I'm giving it weight and prominence.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:32.410" end="00:04:33.910" tts:direction="ltr">Think about it in your own home.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:33.910" end="00:04:35.510" tts:direction="ltr">If you have a blank wall and</p>
        <p begin="00:04:35.510" end="00:04:38.610" tts:direction="ltr">suddenly you place a picture that's framed
<br />on that wall,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:38.610" end="00:04:41.910" tts:direction="ltr">the focus of your audience is going to be
<br />that framed picture.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:41.910" end="00:04:45.160" tts:direction="ltr">They're not going to be like, That
<br />beautiful wall over there.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:45.160" end="00:04:48.560" tts:direction="ltr">No, they're going to focus on to that
<br />framed picture.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:48.560" end="00:04:51.500" tts:direction="ltr">That's a really important concept to say,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:51.500" end="00:04:52.820" tts:direction="ltr">as soon as I do this,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:52.820" end="00:04:56.460" tts:direction="ltr">I'm going to focus a whole bunch of energy
<br />to that space.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:56.460" end="00:04:59.020" tts:direction="ltr">Now, I could use it as a distraction
<br />technique.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:59.020" end="00:05:03.980" tts:direction="ltr">Maybe I've got a hole in my wall or what
<br />have you, and I want to focus.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:03.980" end="00:05:08.520" tts:direction="ltr">I place something that's enclosed so that
<br />my audience goes there first.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:08.520" end="00:05:11.120" tts:direction="ltr">Doesn't mean they won't eventually see the
<br />hole in the wall,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:11.120" end="00:05:13.280" tts:direction="ltr">but they'll see the enclosure first
<br />because</p>
        <p begin="00:05:13.280" end="00:05:16.280" tts:direction="ltr">that's where our eyes and our tension
<br />goes.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:16.280" end="00:05:18.740" tts:direction="ltr">I've got my three groups here my example.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:18.740" end="00:05:20.760" tts:direction="ltr">As soon as I enclose it,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:20.760" end="00:05:23.400" tts:direction="ltr">you can already tell where I'm going.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:23.400" end="00:05:30.300" tts:direction="ltr">That somehow these four dots are tightly
<br />associated versus the other dots.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:30.300" end="00:05:33.040" tts:direction="ltr">These are out and these are in.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:33.040" end="00:05:36.340" tts:direction="ltr">In my cube, all I would need to do is</p>
        <p begin="00:05:36.340" end="00:05:39.780" tts:direction="ltr">enclose a few of these dots to show that
<br />again,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:39.780" end="00:05:41.640" tts:direction="ltr">the relationship happens here,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:41.640" end="00:05:44.960" tts:direction="ltr">and then these are not in the
<br />relationship.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:45.610" end="00:05:49.390" tts:direction="ltr">You can enclose whatever you so choose on
<br />your note card.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:49.390" end="00:05:51.590" tts:direction="ltr">I just want to touch on one other idea,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:51.590" end="00:05:54.710" tts:direction="ltr">which is the idea of closure.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:54.710" end="00:05:57.490" tts:direction="ltr">We don't have the E N in front of us.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:57.490" end="00:06:04.170" tts:direction="ltr">But closure is where our minds will
<br />already create the enclosure.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:04.170" end="00:06:08.950" tts:direction="ltr">For instance, here, I've got three pack
<br />people and I have nothing else.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:08.950" end="00:06:12.510" tts:direction="ltr">I'm using that negative space to create a
<br />closure.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:12.510" end="00:06:17.710" tts:direction="ltr">My mind is already connecting these dots
<br />to create a triangle.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:17.710" end="00:06:19.910" tts:direction="ltr">That is the power of closure,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:19.910" end="00:06:27.470" tts:direction="ltr">and it's a ost principle that exists
<br />without actually placing something.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:27.470" end="00:06:31.470" tts:direction="ltr">I'm not putting an actual square or frame
<br />around that,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:31.470" end="00:06:34.885" tts:direction="ltr">but my mind is creating one naturally.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:34.885" end="00:06:36.780" tts:direction="ltr">When it comes to enclosure,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:36.780" end="00:06:38.260" tts:direction="ltr">here, I've got a line chart.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:38.260" end="00:06:40.140" tts:direction="ltr">We've already talked about white space,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:40.140" end="00:06:41.840" tts:direction="ltr">I can remove that line chart.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:41.840" end="00:06:44.000" tts:direction="ltr">I can not have that enclosure,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:44.000" end="00:06:48.140" tts:direction="ltr">and suddenly it means something different
<br />before and after.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:48.140" end="00:06:50.920" tts:direction="ltr">When it comes to your note cards,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:50.920" end="00:06:52.880" tts:direction="ltr">go ahead and you can connect those dots</p>
        <p begin="00:06:52.880" end="00:06:55.140" tts:direction="ltr">if you want or you can close them if you
<br />want,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:55.140" end="00:06:56.840" tts:direction="ltr">you can color them if you want.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:56.840" end="00:07:00.640" tts:direction="ltr">But just remember that both closure and
<br />enclosure</p>
        <p begin="00:07:00.640" end="00:07:06.160" tts:direction="ltr">are attributes that we have as humans and
<br />what we see.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:06.160" end="00:07:09.580" tts:direction="ltr">The next idea is this idea of continuity</p>
        <p begin="00:07:09.580" end="00:07:13.880" tts:direction="ltr">that we love to be able to see from one
<br />thing to another.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:13.880" end="00:07:16.020" tts:direction="ltr">I've got these two lines,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:16.020" end="00:07:17.940" tts:direction="ltr">dotted lines that are intersecting.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:17.940" end="00:07:23.280" tts:direction="ltr">Now, I want to move from left to right
<br />because that's the way I read,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:23.280" end="00:07:27.420" tts:direction="ltr">and I believe that these two would be
<br />associated with each other.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:27.420" end="00:07:29.360" tts:direction="ltr">If I want to push against that,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:29.360" end="00:07:34.080" tts:direction="ltr">I'm going to have to use another design
<br />element to let my audience know that,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:34.080" end="00:07:36.660" tts:direction="ltr">this may be the natural way you want to
<br />see things,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:36.660" end="00:07:40.335" tts:direction="ltr">but I'm going to have you actually pay
<br />attention to something different.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:40.335" end="00:07:42.870" tts:direction="ltr">So I might use something like color to go
<br />from</p>
        <p begin="00:07:42.870" end="00:07:46.030" tts:direction="ltr">the natural flow from left to right, hey,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:46.030" end="00:07:49.050" tts:direction="ltr">pay attention to this because this is
<br />really the insight</p>
        <p begin="00:07:49.050" end="00:07:53.690" tts:direction="ltr">from left and then reverse back to left to
<br />left.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:53.690" end="00:07:55.550" tts:direction="ltr">When it comes to continuity,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:55.550" end="00:07:58.010" tts:direction="ltr">one way you can apply this in charts</p>
        <p begin="00:07:58.010" end="00:08:01.490" tts:direction="ltr">is that we can think about our axes that
<br />we have,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:01.490" end="00:08:03.250" tts:direction="ltr">we have a y and x axes,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:03.250" end="00:08:05.430" tts:direction="ltr">and those are providing that continuity.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:05.430" end="00:08:07.250" tts:direction="ltr">But if I were to remove those,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:07.250" end="00:08:10.850" tts:direction="ltr">I implicitly know that those already are
<br />there.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:10.850" end="00:08:13.210" tts:direction="ltr">I know that there is an x axis</p>
        <p begin="00:08:13.210" end="00:08:17.270" tts:direction="ltr">and y axis and x axis and that there are
<br />different points.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:17.270" end="00:08:20.210" tts:direction="ltr">Often we don't have to use our axes,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:20.210" end="00:08:23.290" tts:direction="ltr">that's the reason why white space can
<br />work.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:23.290" end="00:08:25.550" tts:direction="ltr">Now, on your cards,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:25.550" end="00:08:26.830" tts:direction="ltr">you can go either direction,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:26.830" end="00:08:28.770" tts:direction="ltr">you can go with the continuity here.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:28.770" end="00:08:32.530" tts:direction="ltr">That's the expectation or you can force
<br />your user to</p>
        <p begin="00:08:32.530" end="00:08:37.130" tts:direction="ltr">reverse by again using another contrasting
<br />element like color.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:37.130" end="00:08:40.670" tts:direction="ltr">The last is principle is this idea of
<br />connection.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:40.670" end="00:08:46.770" tts:direction="ltr">Again, we're going this is the least
<br />prominent,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:46.770" end="00:08:49.210" tts:direction="ltr">and then this is the most.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:49.210" end="00:08:51.410" tts:direction="ltr">We're just going to increase this.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:51.410" end="00:08:57.570" tts:direction="ltr">As soon as I somehow connect my data
